<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-03-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-03-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="642" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d642">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">576.G1/4</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chairman of the Federal Radio Commission</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Sykes</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-24">March 24,
                                1934</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Sykes</hi>: I enclose, for your
                            consideration, a copy of a letter, dated February 9, 1934, from the
                            Secretary General of the League of Nations,<note n="15" xml:id="d642fn15">
                                <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_785">p.
                                785</ref>.</note> together with a copy of its enclosure, a
                            preliminary draft International Agreement for the Use of Broadcasting in
                            the Cause of Peace.<note n="16" xml:id="d642fn16">For text of
                                preliminary draft, see League of Nations, <hi rend="italic">Official
                                    Journal</hi>, February 1934, p. 170.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>In connection with the preparation of a reply, before August 1, 1934, to
                            this communication, I should appreciate receiving such observations or
                            comments on the draft Agreement which the Federal Radio Commission may
                            care to make.</p>
                        <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                        <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>